A Historic Day for Every Somali Citizen –
Dr. Abdillahi Hashi Abib Files Case at
the East African Court of Justice

Today marks a historic turning point for the Somali people. For the first time in our nation’s modern political struggle, a Somali Member of Parliament has been forced - yes, forced - to take the fight for constitutional order outside the borders of Somalia, because no functional or independent constitutional court exists within the country.

I, Dr. Abdillahi Hashi Abib, have officially filed a landmark petition at the East African Court of Justice against the Speaker of the House of the People of the Federal Republic of Somalia, acting under the unlawful direction and political interference of the most corrupt and constitutionally abusive administration Somalia has ever witnessed.

This is not just my case.
This is Somalia’s case.
A case for every citizen who believes in justice, rule of law, and a government that serves the people - not itself.

WHY THIS CASE MATTERS - Because Somalia today has no constitutional court, no independent judiciary capable of defending the Constitution, and no institution willing to restrain blatant abuses of power orchestrated from Villa Somalia under the leadership of Hassan Sheikh Mohamud.

Because the Speaker of the House of the People has allowed himself to become a political weapon rather than a constitutional referee - blocking, delaying, manipulating, and suppressing the mandatory 2026 electoral process.

Because the current regime believes that Somalia is too weak, too afraid, and too silent to challenge them. But today they proved wrong.
A WIN FOR EVERY SOMALI - By filing at the East African Court of Justice, I have broken the political blockade that the President and Speaker have imposed on the Somali people. I have opened a legal pathway so that no corrupt official can shut down. I have taken this fight to a jurisdiction they cannot intimidate, bribe, or control.

Today’s filing is not a personal victory.
It is a national breakthrough.
It restores hope that:

Justice is still possible for Somalis.
The Constitution still means something.
Abusive leaders can still be held accountable beyond Somalia’s borders.
No president, no speaker, and no regime is above the law.

THIS IS WARNING TO THOSE IN POWER - Your manipulation of the elections will not stand. Your misuse of parliament will not be ignored. Your attempt to rule without the consent of the people will not be tolerated. Somalis everywhere - from Mogadishu to Buuhoodle, from Borama to Kismayo, from Nairobi to Minnesota - have now seen that there is a court strong enough to hold you accountable. And that court is no longer in Somalia.

MY MESSAGE TO THE SOMALI PEOPLE - This case belongs to you. This victory belongs to you. And the coming democratic restoration will belong to you.

History will remember today not as the day the system failed, but as the day Somalis rose above a failed system to demand justice.

The corrupt courts in Somalia may be silent - but the East African Court of Justice is not.

And now, Somalia’s fight for the rule of law has begun a new chapter.
📷
Dr. Abdillahi Hashi Abib - BA, MA, MASc, Ph.D
Member of Foreign Affairs Committee
Federal Republic of Somalia the House of People
Mogadishu, Somalia
MP- HOP #201 Awdal Region and Gebileh District
Leader of the Accountability and Transparency Caucus of the House of People
